# Coding Standards

- Readability over cleverness. No surprises file-to-file.
- Consistent style. American spelling.
- Self-documenting names. Small focused functions. Follow project structure.
- Comments explain WHY, constraints, trade-offs — not WHAT.
- Required comments: non-obvious business rules, workarounds, perf/concurrency limits, intentional limits.
- If removing comment no hurt understanding, skip it.
- ALWAYS research about APIs, SDKs, or any packages before using them, use context7 if you have access to it. NEVER assume anything external to the project.
- Do not write divider comments (e.g., // ─── Utilities ───────)

## TypeScript & React

- Zod for all data validation (API in/out, internal transforms).
- TS strict mode. Fix all type errors.
- Types over interfaces.
- No nested ternaries.
- Early returns over nested conditionals. Extract a small function if cleaner.
- Import from React instead of using the global React object (e.g, `React.FC`).
- Function definitions over arrow for root level functions.
- Arrow functions inside of components.
- Let TypeScript infer when possible, avoid unnecessary type annotations.
- Sensible shorthands (e.g., `array.every(Boolean)` instead of `array.every((item) => Boolean(item))`).
- No non-null assertions (`!`) unless absolutely necessary, narrow or validate the value and return or throw an error instead.
- For arguments and props, prefer:
  ```
  type ArgsType = { 
    arg1: string; 
    arg2: number;
  };

  function myFunction(args: ArgsType) {
    const { arg1, arg2 } = args;

    // ...
  }

  type PropsType = { 
    prop1: string; 
    prop2: number;
  };

  function MyComponent(props: PropsType) {
    const { prop1, prop2 } = props;

    // ...
  }
  ```
  over:
  ```
  function myFunction({ arg1, arg2 }: { arg1: string; arg2: number }) {
    // ...
  }
  function MyComponent({ prop1, prop2 }: { prop1: string; prop2: number }) {
    // ...
  }
  ```
- Conditional rendering with syntax, prefer:
  ```
  return <div>{condition && <div>True</div>}</div>;
  ```
  over:
  ```
  return <div>{condition ? <div>True</div> : null}</div>;
  ```
- Prefer defaults over explicit types, for example:
  ```
  const [value, setValue] = useState<string>();
  ```
  over:
  ```
  const [value, setValue] = useState<string | undefined>(undefined);
  ```